Weekly Petroleum Status Report

Brad Horn

29-Mar-2019 Week 13

Summary

Stock Changes

Total commercial petroleum inventories decreased in the last week by 7.2 MMbls. The change is attributed to crude oil alone since stock declines in refined products are offset equally by increased stocks for other fuels.

Crude Oil

U.S. crude oil production averaged 12.2 MMbpd, up from 12.1 MMbpd. Commercial crude oil stocks (excluding the Strategic Petroleum Reserve) by 1.03 MMbbls/day. At 449.5 MMbbls, crude oil inventory are at the 5 year average.

U.S. crude oil refinery inputs averaged 15.8 million barrels per day during the week ending March 29, 2019, which was 18,000 barrels per day more than the previous weeks average. Refineries operated at 86.4% of capacity. U.S. crude oil imports averaged 6.8 million barrels per day last week, up by 223,000 barrels per day from the previous week. Over the past four weeks, crude oil imports averaged about 6.7 million barrels per day, 12.1% less than the same four-week period last year. Exports of 2.7 MMbpd are strong, albeit weaker than the past 2 weeks.

Gasoline

Gasoline production increased last week, averaging 9.8 million barrels per day. Total motor gasoline inventories decreased by 1.8 million barrels last week and are about 2% above the five year average for this time of year. Finished gasoline inventories increased while blending components inventories decreased last week.

Distillates

Distillate fuel production decreased last week, averaging 4.9 million barrels per day. Distillate fuel inventories decreased by 2.0 million barrels last week and are about 6% below the five year average for this time of year.

Spot Prices

WTI at Cushing was priced at $57.81 on March 15, 2019. Brent was price at $65.71 or $7,90 over WTI. The spot price of conventional gasoline in New York Harbor was $1.797 per gallon, $0.090 more than last weeks price and $0.04 lower than a year ago. The spot price for ULSD in NYH was $1.964 per gallon. Current prices are $0.016 below last weeks price.

Notes: Storage withdrawls are shown here in the stock change as positive supply for the market like production; storage injections are shown as negative supply like exports. This is proper for mass balance reporting. The adjustment term is the amount of supply required to balance the market. The volume reflected here is some combination of eia measurement error, pipeline line pack and system losses. A positive adjustment represents new supply for the market and a negative adjustment represents less supply for the market.
